(Intermediate) Quest 5 - Hedera Token Service
Introduction
In this quest, we’ll be covering the second of three Hedera network services - the Hedera Token Service! In particular, we’ll be using it to create and transfer both fungible and non-fungible tokens (NFTs). Before covering the NFT portion of the quest, we’ll also be touching on the concept of decentralized storage, particularly the InterPlanetary File System (IPFS).
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Describe the Hedera Token Service
  • Create and transfer fungible tokens and NFTs using the Hedera Token Service
  • Describe how IPFS works
  • Understand the relationship between NFT images and metadata

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Hedera Token Service
In Quest 1, we learnt that there are three Hedera network services - 1/ Hedera Smart Contract Service, 2/ Hedera Token Service and 3/ Hedera Consensus Service. In Quest 4, we dived into the Hedera Smart Contract Service. In this quest, we’ll be covering our second Hedera network service - the Hedera Token Service (HTS)!
The HTS is a native token service that allows developers to issue, manage, and transfer digital assets. When using HTS, you create these digital assets on the Hedera network. Ownership of digital assets is stored on the ledger and can be transferred and exchanged between users.

The HTS provides developers with an API for integrating the service into their applications. Additionally, HTS offers a variety of tools for developers to help them create and manage their tokens, such as token templates and token management services.

Listed below are some key benefits for choosing Hedera to tokenize your assets:
  1. Programmable - tokens deployed using the HTS offer native programmability, such as atomic swaps and scheduled transactions, for on-chain functionality as efficient as the Hashgraph
  2. Native Tokens - tokens issued with the HTS are native to Hedera, this means that they adopt the same performance, security, and efficiency as HBAR
  3. Low & Predictable Fees - low and predictable transaction fees on the Hedera public network - it costs less than 1¢ USD to transfer any sum of a tokenized asset
  4. Configurable Compliance - key and token configurations at the account level offer the flexibility to meet compliance needs, including KYC verification and freeze, token supply management, transfer, and more
  5. Enterprise Governance - Hedera's decentralized governing body of global organizations ensures network stability, decentralized decision making, and a no-fork guarantee
  6. Security Audit - independent third-party audits performed by FP Complete for the HTS and the Hedera ledger software
Step 2: Difference Between Fungible Tokens & NFTs
Before we continue with the quest, let’s make sure that we understand the difference between fungible tokens and NFTs!
Fungible tokens and NFTs are both types of digital assets, but they have some key differences.

Fungible tokens are interchangeable and identical to each other. They represent a specific amount of value that can be exchanged for goods or services, similar to cash or other forms of currency. Examples of fungible tokens include cryptocurrency, such as Bitcoin and Ethereum, and stablecoins, which are digital assets pegged to the value of a fiat currency or other stable asset.

On the other hand, NFTs are unique digital assets that cannot be replicated or replaced. They represent ownership of something that is one-of-a-kind, such as a digital art piece, a collectible, or a virtual item in a game. Each NFT is unique, and the ownership of an NFT can be verified on a blockchain. They are often used to represent ownership of virtual assets such as digital art, music, videos and other digital collectibles.

Fungible tokens are typically used for transactions involving the exchange of money or assets, while NFTs are used to represent unique digital assets that can be bought, sold, and traded like physical collectibles.

Now that we got that squared off, let’s proceed to the next step where we’ll be getting an overview of what we’ll be covering in this quest.
Step 3: Quest Scenario
In the subsequent steps, we’ll be going through how we can use the Hedera Token Service APIs to create and transfer fungible tokens as well as NFTs. Let’s contextualize our learning by using the following scenario.
There are two characters in this scenario - Alice and Bob. Alice is a freelance worker and she charges for her work by the hour. Bob is one of Alice’s loyal customers. Recently, she’s found that it's been difficult to keep track of the people who’ve been hiring her for her work. Thus, she made the decision to tokenize her free hours to be represented as fungible tokens.

Here’s how it’ll look like - Alice will create a new fungible token called Alice Hours (AHOUR). If Bob wants to purchase 4 hours of Alice’s time, Bob will buy 4 AHOUR tokens from Alice. Since Bob has 4 AHOUR tokens, it signifies that Bob has paid for 4 hours of Alice’s time. In the fungible token portion of this quest, we’ll be creating this token and transferring it from Alice to Bob.

Over some time, Alice recognized that there are a small group of people (such as Bob) that have been regularly supporting her. She, in turn, would like to give them a token of appreciation. She decides to create a collection of NFTs titled Alice NFT (ANFT) - whoever owns one will be entitled to a 40% discount whenever the individual contracts Alice for her service. In the NFT portion of the quest, we’ll be creating this NFT collection, minting an NFT and transferring it from Alice to Bob.
Step 4: Fungible Tokens vs NFTs
As a reminder, we can create two types of tokens using the Hedera Token Service: fungible and non-fungible tokens. The type for a fungible token is FUNGIBLE_COMMON and is set when building a TokenCreateTransaction() using TokenType.FungibleCommon. A non-fungible token type is NON_FUNGIBLE_UNIQUE and is set using TokenType.NonFungibleUnique.
As we’ll soon come to learn, the processes of creating and transferring fungible tokens and NFTs share many similarities. Listed below are the steps required (along with their respective APIs) that will be used in each category:

Fungible Tokens
  1. Create token - TokenCreateTransaction()
  2. Associate token to user account - TokenAssociateTransaction()
  3. Transfer token - TransferTransaction()

NFTs
  1. Create token - TokenCreateTransaction()
  2. Mint NFT- TokenMintTransaction()
  3. Associate token to user account - TokenAssociateTransaction()
  4. Transfer token - TransferTransaction()

You don’t need to commit anything to memory now, but just take note of the similarities between the two as we progress along the quest. Alright, now let’s start with the fungible token portion of the quest!

We’ll be making use of the project repository stackup-hedera that was created in Quest 3. If you have completed Quest 3 or Quest 4, then feel free to proceed with the remainder of this step. require("dotenv").config(); const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); const aliceId = AccountId.fromString(process.env.ALICE_ACCOUNT_ID); const aliceKey = PrivateKey.fromString(process.env.ALICE_PRIVATE_KEY); const bobId = AccountId.fromString(process.env.BOB_ACCOUNT_ID); const bobKey = PrivateKey.fromString(process.env.BOB_PRIVATE_KEY); const client = Client.forTestnet().setOperator(aliceId, aliceKey); async function createFungibleToken() {  // Part 1 - Create token  // Part 2 - Associate token to user account  // Part 3 - Check balance (before)  // Part 4 - Transfer tokens  // Part 5 - Check balance (after)  client.close(); } createFungibleToken();

This code is largely similar to what we did for both Quest 3 and Quest 4. To recap, what we’re doing here is grabbing our Hedera testnet account ID and private key from our .env file and creating a client for testnet which establishes a connection with the Hedera test network.

We’re using PrivateKey.fromString() and AccountId.fromString(). PrivateKey.fromString() is used to construct a privateKey object from a string whereas AccountId.fromString() is used to construct an accountID object from a string.

Step 7: Fungible Token Part 1 - Creating a Token
With our project environment set up properly now, the first thing we’ll be doing is creating the token. We can do this with the TokenCreateTransaction() API. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 1 - Create token in your script.
let tokenCreateTx = await new TokenCreateTransaction()   .setTokenName("Alice Hours")   .setTokenSymbol("AHOUR")   .setTokenType(TokenType.FungibleCommon)   .setDecimals(1)   .setInitialSupply(1000)   .setTreasuryAccountId(aliceId)   .setSupplyType(TokenSupplyType.Infinite)   .setSupplyKey(aliceKey)   .freezeWith(client);  let tokenCreateSign = await tokenCreateTx.sign(aliceKey);  let tokenCreateSubmit = await tokenCreateSign.execute(client);  let tokenCreateRx = await tokenCreateSubmit.getReceipt(client);  let tokenId = tokenCreateRx.tokenId;  console.log(`- Created token with ID: ${tokenId}`);

Essentially, what we’re doing here is calling the TokenCreateTransaction() API to create a fungible token as well as configure its properties. At a minimum, this API requires setting a name, symbol, and treasury account ID. All other fields are optional; if they’re not specified, default values will be used.

As mentioned, we have to assign an account to become the treasury when creating a new token - this account will be the holder of this new token. You set the treasury account by calling .setTreasuryAccountId() and passing in the account id of the account you’re appointing as the treasury. You then have to ensure you sign the transaction with that same account id. Since we are minting tokens, we’ll need to set a supply key. The supply key can change the total supply of a token and is used to authorize token mint and burn transactions; without it, we can’t mint/burn tokens. 

Another thing to note here is the relationship between .setDecimals() and .setInitialSupply(). Since we input 1 into .setDecimals(), what we input into .setInitialSupply() should be 10 times more than what we plan for the initial supply to be; this is to account for the decimal places. So in our case, although we input 1000 into .setInitialSupply(), we can expect to only have a starting supply of 100 tokens, but 1000 of the smallest possible unit (0.1) of a token.

After preparing the transaction, we sign it with Alice’s private key and submit it to the Hedera network. Lastly, we get the receipt of the transaction and print out the token ID of our newly created fungible token.

Since we used quite a few new modules, let’s make sure to include them as part of our script’s dependencies. Replace line 2 of your script with the code below.

const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client, TokenCreateTransaction, TokenType, TokenSupplyType } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Now let’s test it out! Open a terminal and navigate to the stackup-hedera directory. Run the command below in your terminal.

node fungible-token.js

If you’ve followed the previous steps correctly, your terminal output should be similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. Also, if you refresh your Hashpack wallet (make sure you’re in Alice’s account), you should see our new token: Alice Hours! Again, you can refer to ‘Expected output’ for a reference on what you can expect to see.

Step 8: Fungible Token Part 2 - Associating Tokens to an Account
In Hedera, before an account can receive or send a specific token ID, the account must become “associated” with the token. This is to prevent the situation where a user’s account gets sent unwanted tokens. This feature adds an extra layer of security to user accounts in Hedera (especially relevant in light of recent events).
Associating tokens to user accounts is a simple task with the TokenAssociateTransaction() API. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 2 - Associate token to user account.

let associateBobTx = await new TokenAssociateTransaction().setAccountId(bobId).setTokenIds([tokenId]).freezeWith(client);  // sign with the private key of the account that is being associated to the token  await associateBobTx.sign(bobKey);  let associateBobTxSubmit = await associateBobTx.execute(client);  let associateBobRx = await associateBobTxSubmit.getReceipt(client);  console.log(`- Token association with Bob's account: ${associateBobRx.status}\n`);

When we call the TokenAssociateTransaction() API, we’re basically telling the Hedera network that we want to associate Bob (bobId) with the fungible token (tokenId). Note that we sign the transaction with Bob’s private key (bobKey); this makes sense since Bob should be the only person that has the authority to associate tokens that enter his wallet.

Afterwards, we submit the transaction to the Hedera network and get its receipt. If the token association is a success, we should expect associateBobRx.status to return TRUE.

Since we used the TokenAssociateTransaction module, let’s add that to line 2 of our script, similar to how we added the other modules in the previous step. This is what the complete import/require statement at the top of our script looks like currently:

const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client, TokenCreateTransaction, TokenType, TokenSupplyType, TokenAssociateTransaction } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");
Step 9: Fungible Token Part 3 - Transferring Tokens
If you’ve completed Quest 3, you would already know the APIs that we’ll be using here! We’ll be using two APIs - AccountBalanceQuery() and TransferTransaction(). The first checks the token balance of the accounts and the latter facilitates the transfer of tokens. 
We start off by printing out the AHOUR token balance of both Alice and Bob using AccountBalanceQuery(). We should expect Alice to have a balance of 1000 units of AHOUR tokens and Bob to have 0 units of AHOUR tokens. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 3 - Check balance (before). 

var aliceBefore = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(aliceId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Alice balance: ${aliceBefore.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} units of token ID ${tokenId}`);  var bobBefore = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(bobId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Bob's balance: ${bobBefore.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} units of token ID ${tokenId}`);

Recall that in our scenario, Bob wants to purchase 4 hours of Alice’s time. Since the AHOUR token has 1 decimal place, we’ll need to input 40 into TransferTransaction() if we want to transfer 4 AHOUR tokens from Alice to Bob (i.e. transferring 40 units of 0.1 AHOUR tokens). Note that we’re using .addTokenTransfer() here instead of .addHbarTransfer() as we did previously in Quest 3 since we’re not transferring HBAR. 

After that is done, we get the receipt of the transaction and print out its status. If the transaction went through, we should expect TRUE to be returned. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 4 - Transfer tokens. 

let tokenTransferTx = await new TransferTransaction()   .addTokenTransfer(tokenId, aliceId, -40)   .addTokenTransfer(tokenId, bobId, 40)   .freezeWith(client)   .sign(aliceKey);  let tokenTransferSubmit = await tokenTransferTx.execute(client);  let tokenTransferRx = await tokenTransferSubmit.getReceipt(client);  console.log(`\n- AHOUR transfer from Alice to Bob: ${tokenTransferRx.status} \n`);

Lastly, we print out the AHOUR token balance of both accounts again. This time, we should expect Alice to have 960 units of AHOUR tokens and Bob to have 40 units of AHOUR tokens. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 5 - Check balance (after). 

var aliceAfter = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(aliceId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Alice balance: ${aliceAfter.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} units of token ID ${tokenId}`);  var bobAfter = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(bobId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Bob's balance: ${bobAfter.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} units of token ID ${tokenId}`);

Remember, before we can run our script, we’ll need to add in the new modules we’ve just introduced - AccountBalanceQuery and TransferTransaction. Add these to line 2 of our script, similar to how we’ve added the modules in the previous steps. This is what the complete import/require statement at the top of our script looks like currently:

const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client, TokenCreateTransaction, TokenType, TokenSupplyType, TokenAssociateTransaction, AccountBalanceQuery, TransferTransaction, } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Now let’s see if our script works as expected! Run the command below in your terminal. If you’ve followed along correctly so far, you should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. 

node fungible-token.js

Open up your Hashpack wallet and check both accounts too! Don’t worry if you see multiple ‘Alice Hours’ tokens; that’s because each time you run your script, you create a new fungible token. To remove all the unwanted tokens in your Hashpack wallet, press on ‘Manage’ and toggle off all the unwanted tokens, leaving the one at the bottom toggled on (this is the most recent Alice Hours token). You should see that in Bob’s wallet, there are 4 Alice Hours tokens and in Alice’s wallet, there are 96 Alice Hours tokens. 

Awesome! To recap, we’ve just covered how we can use an assortment of APIs from the Hedera Token service for Alice to create her own fungible token and transfer it to someone else. Now let’s move on to the second half of this quest - creating, minting and transferring an NFT!

Step 10: Introduction to IPFS & Storing NFT Information
InterPlanetary File System (IPFS) is protocol, hypermedia and file sharing peer-to-peer network for storing and sharing data in a distributed file system. It allows users to share and access files and data on a peer-to-peer network, rather than relying on a centralized server.
IPFS uses a content-addressable approach, meaning that files are identified by their content, rather than by their location. This allows for faster and more efficient retrieval of files, as well as the ability to access files even if the original server is offline. It also provides a high degree of security, as the files are spread across multiple nodes and are not controlled by a single entity. Refer here if you would like to find out more about IPFS.

In the Web3 world, a common use case of IPFS is hosting the metadata and media files of the digital asset. Let’s use the example of the most common media file of NFTs - images. 



Storing images in the blockchain is extremely pricey due to its large file size. Therefore the standard practice is to instead store the images off-chain (typically on a decentralized storage platform such as IPFS) and make reference to that instead. However, an NFT typically does not make reference to the image directly; it typically points to a metadata file (that also resides in the decentralized storage platform), and the metadata file is the one that points towards the image file. 

The purpose of the metadata file is to contain additional information regarding the NFT such as the name of the collection, the serial number of the NFT, description, format, etc. When minting an IPFS URI is pointing to the metadata file. We’ll be seeing this interaction for ourselves firsthand later on as we’re covering the NFT portion of the quest.
Step 11: NFT Part 1 - Creating a Token
We’ll start by creating a new script called non-fungible-token.js in our project repository. Then, we’ll paste in the same starting code as we used for the earlier section. Copy the code below and paste it into the file you just created.
require("dotenv").config(); const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); const aliceId = AccountId.fromString(process.env.ALICE_ACCOUNT_ID); const aliceKey = PrivateKey.fromString(process.env.ALICE_PRIVATE_KEY); const bobId = AccountId.fromString(process.env.BOB_ACCOUNT_ID); const bobKey = PrivateKey.fromString(process.env.BOB_PRIVATE_KEY); const client = Client.forTestnet().setOperator(aliceId, aliceKey); async function createNonFungibleToken() {  // Part 1 - Create token  // Part 2 - Mint token  // Part 3 - Associate token to user account  // Part 4 - Transfer token  client.close(); } createNonFungibleToken();

After you’ve done that, we’re going to start by creating the token. As mentioned earlier, this will very closely mirror what we did for creating fungible tokens. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 1 - Create token in your script.

let nftCreate = await new TokenCreateTransaction()   .setTokenName("Alice NFT")   .setTokenSymbol("ANFT")   .setTokenType(TokenType.NonFungibleUnique)   .setDecimals(0)   .setInitialSupply(0)   .setTreasuryAccountId(aliceId)   .setSupplyType(TokenSupplyType.Finite)   .setMaxSupply(10)   .setSupplyKey(aliceKey)   .freezeWith(client);  let nftCreateTxSign = await nftCreate.sign(aliceKey);  let nftCreateSubmit = await nftCreateTxSign.execute(client);  let nftCreateRx = await nftCreateSubmit.getReceipt(client);  let tokenId = nftCreateRx.tokenId;  console.log(`- Created NFT with Token ID: ${tokenId} \n`);

We create the NFT collection using the TokenCreateTransaction() API. Unlike creating a fungible token, we have to set the initial supply to be 0 - we do so with .setInitialSupply(0). Another difference is that for NFTs, we’re required to specify a maximum supply. In our case, we’ve set that to 10 by using .setMaxSupply(10).

After submitting the transaction above to the Hedera network, we call .getReceipt on the transaction response. From the receipt, we can extract the tokenId.

Same as always, we’ll need to import the modules used. Replace line 2 of your script with the code below.

const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client, TokenCreateTransaction, TokenType, TokenSupplyType } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Run the command below in your terminal to test out the script!

node non-fungible-token.js

You should be able to get an output that states the tokenId of the newly created NFT collection. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference.

Step 12: NFT Part 2 - Minting a Token
Noticed earlier that we set the initial supply to be zero? That’s because when it comes to NFTs, the starting supply must always be zero; only after the token is created can you start minting each NFT using the TokenMintTransaction() API. Recall that the supply key is required to sign the transaction that is going to mint the token since the supply key is the only one authorized to mint tokens. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 2 - Mint token.
const CID = "ipfs://QmaSH6QrD7f7NE7yPrYchJnMJ3uQEvgWuSzzUpRdmSvxhA/";  let mintTx = await new TokenMintTransaction()   .setTokenId(tokenId)   .setMetadata([Buffer.from(CID)])   .freezeWith(client);  let mintTxSign = await mintTx.sign(aliceKey);  let mintTxSubmit = await mintTxSign.execute(client);  let mintRx = await mintTxSubmit.getReceipt(client);  console.log(`- Created NFT ${tokenId} with serial: ${mintRx.serials[0].low} \n`);

As mentioned in Step 10, the NFT points towards the metadata.json file, which in turn points towards the image file. Thus, when we’re minting the NFT token, we need to specify the content identifier (CID) of the metadata file. You can think of the CID as the address of the file in IPFS.



If you view the contents of the metadata file in your browser, you’ll see that it is a JSON file containing information regarding the NFT as well as the URL that points towards the image file.



If you visit the URL stated in the metadata file, you’ll be able to see the image that we’ll be using for our NFT!﻿
Step 13: NFT Part 3 - Associating Token To User Account
We learned earlier that before receiving a token, the account must first be associated with that token’s tokenId. Same as before, we’ll be using the TokenAssociateTransaction() API. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 3 - Associate token to user account.
let associateAliceTx = await new TokenAssociateTransaction().setAccountId(bobId).setTokenIds([tokenId]).freezeWith(client).sign(bobKey);  let associateAliceTxSubmit = await associateAliceTx.execute(client);  let associateAliceRx = await associateAliceTxSubmit.getReceipt(client);  console.log(`- NFT association with Bob's account: ${associateAliceRx.status}\n`);

Recall that since Bob is the one receiving the token, Bob’s account must sign the transaction. Therefore, we call .sign() on the transaction and pass in Bob’s private key.
Step 14: NFT Part 4 - Transferring the Token
Now for the last part - transferring the NFT! Again, the code used here is largely the same as what we used for transferring the fungible tokens. We’ll be using the AccountBalanceQuery() API to query for the token balance of the accounts and TransferTransaction() to transfer the NFT from Alice to Bob. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 4 - Transfer token.
// balance check (before)  var balanceCheckTx = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(aliceId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Alice balance: ${balanceCheckTx.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} NFTs of ID ${tokenId}`);  var balanceCheckTx = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(bobId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Bob's balance: ${balanceCheckTx.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} NFTs of ID ${tokenId}`);  let tokenTransferTx = await new TransferTransaction().addNftTransfer(tokenId, 1, aliceId, bobId).freezeWith(client).sign(aliceKey);  let tokenTransferSubmit = await tokenTransferTx.execute(client);  let tokenTransferRx = await tokenTransferSubmit.getReceipt(client);  console.log(`\n- NFT transfer from Treasury to Alice: ${tokenTransferRx.status} \n`);  // balance check (after)  var balanceCheckTx = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(aliceId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Alice balance: ${balanceCheckTx.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} NFTs of ID ${tokenId}`);  var balanceCheckTx = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(bobId).execute(client);  console.log(`- Bob's balance: ${balanceCheckTx.tokens._map.get(tokenId.toString())} NFTs of ID ${tokenId}`);

Note that when we use the TransferTransaction() API, we use .addNftTransfer() instead since well, we’re dealing with NFTs here. If all goes well, we should expect to see the ending balance of Alice to be 0 and Bob to be 1.

Last step before testing out our script - importing the modules. Replace line 2 of your script with the code below.

const { AccountId, PrivateKey, Client, TokenCreateTransaction, TokenType, TokenSupplyType, TokenMintTransaction, TransferTransaction, AccountBalanceQuery, TokenAssociateTransaction, } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Now let’s run our script and see if our code works! Run the command below in your terminal.

node non-fungible-token.js



Your terminal output should be similar to the image shown above. Now open your Hashpack wallet, change to Bob’s account and open up the ‘NFTS’ tab. You should be able to see our newly minted NFT! Step 15: Summary
We’ve covered quite a bit in this quest so let’s go through a summary of what we covered to consolidate our learning! In this quest, we covered the Hedera Token Service, one of the three Hedera network services. Following our scenario, we’ve seen how Alice used the Hedera Token Service to create a fungible token (Alice Hours) as well as an NFT collection (Alice NFT) and transfer some of these tokens to Bob.
Here’s a quick summary of the points covered in this quest!
  • Hedera Token Service (HTS) makes it easy for developers to issue native tokens at low predictable costs with scalable performance and configurability. It offers developers a way to manage and transfer tokens
  • The TokenCreateTransaction() API is used to create fungible tokens as well as NFTs. To create an NFT you must .setTokenType() and pass in TokenType.FungibleUnique. To create a fungible token you can set the token type to TokenType.FungibleCommon. If you do not specify a token type, then a fungible token is created by default
  • Before an account can receive a token (both fungible and non-fungible), it has to be associated with the token
  • IPFS is a decentralized file storage protocol. NFT media files as well as its metadata are typically stored in IPFS
  • The typical workflow of creating and transferring a fungible token is create token with an initial supply -> associate -> transfer
  • The typical workflow of creating and transferring an NFT is create -> mint -> associate -> transfer
